RacePlex
========

RacePlex is a fork of Dove's DataViewer.

    Upstream:  Dove's DataViewer  (also published as "LapWing")
    Author:    TheAngryRaven
    Source:    https://github.com/TheAngryRaven/DovesDataViewer
    Licence:   GPL-3.0-or-later

RacePlex is likewise licensed GPL-3.0-or-later. See LICENSE for the full text.

Nearly all of the telemetry engine — the VBO, NMEA, UBX, MoTeC, AiM, Alfano and iRacing parsers,
the lap-crossing detection, the sector and optimal-lap math, the chart and map layers, the video
overlay renderer, and the offline-first PWA architecture — is upstream's work. RacePlex would not
exist without it, and we are grateful for it.


Statement of changes (GPL-3.0 §5(a))
------------------------------------

Fork established 2026-07-12 by the RacePlex contributors.

Changes made by RacePlex relative to upstream:

  * Reoriented the project from cars and karts to electric skateboards: course models suited to
    point-to-point runs (hill runs, slalom, drag) rather than closed circuits, and telemetry
    channels specific to electric skateboards (VESC motor current, battery sag, ERPM).

  * Added device support absent upstream: GPX import, RaceBox CSV import (including automatic
    detection of the speed column's unit, which RaceBox does not record in the file), and
    RaceChrono CSV v3 import.

  * Added reconstruction of timing lines from GPX waypoints, so a rider gets working lap timing
    without drawing a start/finish line by hand.

  * Added generic Web Bluetooth support for third-party GPS loggers (RaceBox, Dragy). Upstream's
    Bluetooth implementation is specific to its own DovesDataLogger hardware.

  * Added docs/research/FORMATS.md, a sourced reference for the telemetry formats involved.

  * Committed to remaining free and fully local: no subscription tiers, no feature gating, no
    required backend.

RacePlex is an independent project and makes no commitment to contribute these changes upstream.
Where they are useful to upstream, upstream is welcome to take them — that is what the licence is
for.

